[[File:The A299, towards the junction with the A2- M2 - geograph.org.uk - 156544.jpg|thumb|right|The A299, towards the junction with the A2/M2]]

The '''A299''', better known as the '''Thanet Way''', is a major road in the county of [[Kent]], England, and runs from Brenley Corner near [[Faversham]] (where it merges into the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2]]) to [[Ramsgate]] via [[Whitstable]] and [[Herne Bay, Kent|Herne Bay]]. It is predominantly used for [[freight]] traffic to [[Port of Ramsgate|Ramsgate Harbour]] and local traffic to [[Isle of Thanet|Thanet]],<ref name="kcc"/> and is {{convert|22|mi}} long.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://maps.google.co.uk/maps?saddr=51.334526,1.389384&daddr=Thanet+Way%2FA299&hl=en&ll=51.315593,0.979843&spn=0.240766,0.616608&sll=51.30387,0.928345&sspn=0.007526,0.019269&geocode=FX5NDwMdSDMVAA%3BFb3VDgMdWSoOAA&t=h&mra=ls&z=11 |title=Directions to Thanet Way/A299 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |work= |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> It also provides access to [[Manston Airport]].

==History==
The A299 was originally allocated to the original road from Faversham to Herne Bay, via Graveney, Seasalter and Whitstable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/maps/index.php?view=51.35236,0.98824&map=NPEMap&zoom=7&layer=9|title=Quarter Inch Map of Great Britain|publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]]|date=1930|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> Most of the modern route was constructed in the early 1930s as an unemployment relief project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1931/feb/12/unemployment-1#S5CV0248P0_19310212_HOC_434|title=UNEMPLOYMENT : Captain Harold Balfour |publisher=Hansard |date=12 Feb 1931 |accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1930/jan/21/kent|title=Kent|publisher=Hansard|date=21 January 1930|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> Prior to this, all traffic from the west to the Isle of Thanet had to go via [[Canterbury]].

The A299 was upgraded between 1989 and 1997 to dual carriageway for almost its entire length.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1994/may/09/a299|title=A99|publisher=Hansard|date=9 May 1994|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="kcc">{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1996/dec/04/kent-capital-challenge|title=Kent Capital Challenge|date=4 December 1996|publisher=Hansard|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> Whitstable and Herne Bay were bypassed, with the old road becoming the A2990, and the A299 to the west of Whitstable and east of Herne Bay received an online upgrade. 

The original Thanet Way project, and hence the A299, used to end near [[Monkton, Kent|Monkton]], where the A253 once continued to Ramsgate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/maps/index.php?view=51.36018,1.30289&map=NPEMap&zoom=7&layer=1|title=1 Inch Seventh Series Map|publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]]|date=1960|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> This section of road has been renumbered as an extension of the A299 to [[Port of Ramsgate|Ramsgate Harbour]].  

The section from Minster roundabout to the Lord of the Manor roundabout was diverted on to a new dual carriageway during 2009-12, constructed as part of East Kent access phase 2 to provide better access to Manston Airport and the [[Pfizer]] complex at [[Sandwich, Kent|Sandwich]]. It was opened by [[Norman Baker]] on 23 May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kent.gov.uk/roads_and_transport/highway_improvements/major_transport_schemes/current_schemes/east_kent_phase_2.aspx |title=East Kent Access Phase 2 |publisher=Kent County Council |date= |accessdate=13 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311231554/http://kent.gov.uk/roads_and_transport/highway_improvements/major_transport_schemes/current_schemes/east_kent_phase_2.aspx |archivedate=11 March 2013 }}</ref>

