{{Italic title}} {{Taxobox | name = ''Amalgaviridae'' | virus_group = iii | ordo = ''Unassigned'' | familia = '''''Amalgaviridae''''' | subdivision_ranks = Genera | subdivision = * ''Amalgavirus'' }}
'''''Amalgaviridae''''' is a family of [[Double-stranded RNA viruses|double-stranded]] [[RNA virus]]es that has one genus: ''Amalgavirus''. Members of both the family and the genus are referred to as amalgaviruses. There are currently four recognized species of the family: ''Blueberry latent virus'',<ref name=pmid208 >{{Cite journal | pmid = 20888379 | year = 2011 | author1 = Martin | first1 = R. R. | title = Blueberry latent virus: An amalgam of the Partitiviridae and Totiviridae | journal = Virus Research | volume = 155 | issue = 1 | pages = 175–80 | last2 = Zhou | first2 = J | last3 = Tzanetakis | first3 = I. E. | doi = 10.1016/j.virusres.2010.09.020 }}</ref> ''Rhododendron virus A'',<ref name=pmid207 >{{Cite journal | pmid = 20721591 | year = 2010 | author1 = Sabanadzovic | first1 = S | title = A novel monopartite dsRNA virus from rhododendron | journal = Archives of Virology | volume = 155 | issue = 11 | pages = 1859–63 | last2 = Abou Ghanem-Sabanadzovic | first2 = N | last3 = Valverde | first3 = R. A. | doi = 10.1007/s00705-010-0770-5 }}</ref> ''Southern tomato virus'',<ref name=pmid191 >{{Cite journal | pmid = 19118586 | year = 2009 | author1 = Sabanadzovic | first1 = S | title = Southern tomato virus: The link between the families Totiviridae and Partitiviridae | journal = Virus Research | volume = 140 | issue = 1-2 | pages = 130–7 | last2 = Valverde | first2 = R. A. | last3 = Brown | first3 = J. K. | last4 = Martin | first4 = R. R. | last5 = Tzanetakis | first5 = I. E. | doi = 10.1016/j.virusres.2008.11.018 }}</ref> the [[type species]] of ''Amalgavirus'', and ''Vicia cryptic virus M''.<ref name=pmid194 >{{Cite journal | pmid = 19472044 | year = 2009 | author1 = Liu | first1 = W | title = A double-stranded RNA as the genome of a potential virus infecting Vicia faba | journal = Virus Genes | volume = 39 | issue = 1 | pages = 126–31 | last2 = Chen | first2 = J | doi = 10.1007/s11262-009-0362-1 }}</ref> The family and genus are called ''amalga'', from ''amalgam'', due to the viruses possessing characteristics of both [[Partitiviridae|partitiviruses]] and [[Totiviridae|totiviruses]], indicating a likely genetic relation to those two families.<ref name=pmid208 /><ref name=pmid191 /> Members of this family infect [[plant]]s and are [[Vertical transmission|transmitted vertically]] via [[seed]]s.<ref name=pmid208 /> Their genomes are [[monopartite]], about 3.5 [[kilobase]]s in length,<ref name=pmid207 /><ref name=pmid191 /> and contain two partially overlapping [[open reading frame]]s, encoding the RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (RdRp) and a putative capsid protein.<ref name=pmid191 /><ref name=pmid194 />
==Evolution==
It has been suggested that amalgaviruses have evolved via recombination between viruses with double-stranded and negative-strand RNA genomes.<ref name=Krupovic2015>{{cite journal|vauthors=Krupovic M, Dolja VV, Koonin EV |title=Plant viruses of the Amalgaviridae family evolved via recombination between viruses with double-stranded and negative-strand RNA genomes|journal=Biol Direct|date=2015|volume=10|issue=1|page=12|doi=10.1186/s13062-015-0047-8|pmid=25886840|pmc=4377212}}</ref> Specifically, phylogenetic analyses have shown that the amalgavirus RdRps form a sister clade to the corresponding proteins of partitiviruses ([[Partitiviridae]]) which have segmented (bipartite) dsRNA genomes and infect plants, fungi and protists.<ref name=pmid208 /><ref name=pmid207 /><ref name=pmid191 /><ref name=Krupovic2015 /> By contrast, the putative capsid protein of amalgaviruses is homologous to the nucleocapsid proteins of negative-strand RNA viruses of the genera [[Phlebovirus]] ([[Bunyaviridae]]) and [[Tenuivirus]].<ref name=Krupovic2015 />
