{{bacteria-stub}}

The '''hypothalamic–pituitary–somatotropic axis''' ('''HPS axis'''), or '''hypothalamic–pituitary–somatic axis''', also known as the '''hypothalamic–pituitary–growth axis''', is a [[hypothalamic–pituitary axis]] which includes the [[secretion]] of [[growth hormone]] (GH; somatotropin) from the [[somatotrope]]s of the [[pituitary gland]] into the [[circulatory system|circulation]] and the subsequent stimulation of [[insulin-like growth factor 1]] (IGF-1; somatomedin-1) [[biosynthesis|production]] by GH in [[tissue (biology)|tissue]]s such as, namely, the [[liver]].<ref name="Jameson2013">{{cite book|author=J. Larry Jameson|title=Harrison's Endocrinology, 3E|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yFzFQMCMOGYC|date=22 March 2013|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|isbn=978-0-07-181487-4|page=16}}</ref><ref name="Straub2015">{{cite book|author=Rainer Straub|title=The Origin of Chronic Inflammatory Systemic Diseases and their Sequelae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kaAGBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA70|date=8 April 2015|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-12-803322-7|pages=70–}}</ref><ref name="ButteryLindsay2016">{{cite book|author1=P.J. Buttery|author2=D.B. Lindsay|author3=N.B. Haynes|title=Control and Manipulation of Animal Growth: Proceedings of Previous Easter Schools in Agricultural Science|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ha_YBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA259|date=22 January 2016|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-1-4831-6186-0|pages=259–}}</ref> Other [[hypothalamic–pituitary hormone]]s such as [[growth hormone-releasing hormone]] (GHRH; somatocrinin), [[growth hormone-inhibiting hormone]] (GHIH; somatostatin), and [[ghrelin]] ({{abbr|GHS|growth hormone secretagogue}}) are involved in the control of GH secretion from the pituitary gland.<ref name="Jameson2013" /> The HPS axis is involved in postnatal [[human development (biology)|human growth]].<ref name="Jameson2013" /> Individuals with [[growth hormone deficiency]] or [[Laron syndrome]] ({{abbrlink|GHR|growth hormone receptor}} insensitivity) show symptoms like [[short stature]], [[dwarfism]] and [[obesity]], but are also protected from some forms of [[cancer]].<ref name="pmid25905205">{{cite journal | vauthors = De Groot LJ, Chrousos G, Dungan K, Feingold KR, Grossman A, Hershman JM, Koch C, Korbonits M, McLachlan R, New M, Purnell J, Rebar R, Singer F, Vinik A, Murray PG, Clayton PE | title = Disorders of Growth Hormone in Childhood | journal = | volume = | issue = | pages = | year = 2000| pmid = 25905205 | doi = | url = }}</ref><ref name="pmid28528685">{{cite journal | vauthors = Laron Z, Kauli R, Lapkina L, Werner H | title = IGF-I deficiency, longevity and cancer protection of patients with Laron syndrome | journal = Mutat. Res. | volume = 772 | issue = | pages = 123–133 | year = 2017 | pmid = 28528685 | doi = 10.1016/j.mrrev.2016.08.002 | url = }}</ref> Conversely, [[acromegaly]] and [[gigantism]] are conditions of GH and IGF-1 excess usually due to a [[pituitary tumor]], and are characterized by [[overgrowth syndrome|overgrowth]] and [[tall stature]].<ref name="pmid28613738">{{cite journal | vauthors = Adigun O, Mesfin F | title = Acromegaly | journal = | volume = | issue = | pages = | year = 2017| pmid = 28613738 | doi = | url = }}</ref><ref name="pmid25905378">{{cite journal | vauthors = De Groot LJ, Chrousos G, Dungan K, Feingold KR, Grossman A, Hershman JM, Koch C, Korbonits M, McLachlan R, New M, Purnell J, Rebar R, Singer F, Vinik A, Eugster E | title = Gigantism | journal = | volume = | issue = | pages = | year = 2000| pmid = 25905378 | doi = | url = }}</ref>

