"'''The Magic Cauldron'''" is an essay by [[Eric S. Raymond]] on the [[open-source]] economic model.<ref>
*{{cite book|editor-last1=Himma|editor-link1=Kenneth Einar Himma|editor-first1=Kenneth E.|editor-last2=Tavani|editor-first2=Herman T.|title=The Handbook of Information and Computer Ethics|year=2008|publisher=Wiley-Interscience|isbn=0471799599|pages=261–263|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZC7SDyPZUMoC&pg=PA261&dq=%22Magic+Cauldron%22+Raymond&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qxMpU9XWHam_0gHFo4HQDQ&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22Magic%20Cauldron%22%20Raymond&f=false}}
*{{cite news|title=Informationweek, Issues 742-750|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qEJVAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Magic+Cauldron%22+Raymond&dq=%22Magic+Cauldron%22+Raymond&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YRUpU4HbN4eX0gH23YCoDA&ved=0CFsQ6AEwCTge|accessdate=19 March 2014|newspaper=InformationWeek (p 75)|year=1999}}
*{{cite book|last=Brian Jepson, Joan Peckham|first=Ram Sadasiv|title=Database application programming with Linux|year=2000|publisher=John Wiley|isbn=9780471355496|page=143|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dM5QAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Magic+Cauldron%22+Raymond&dq=%22Magic+Cauldron%22+Raymond&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YRUpU4HbN4eX0gH23YCoDA&ved=0CFUQ6AEwCDge}}
*{{cite journal|last=Fuggetta|first=Alfonso|title=Open source software––an evaluation|journal=Journal of Systems and Software|year=2003|volume=66|issue=1|page=85|doi=10.1016/S0164-1212(02)00065-1}}</ref> It can be read freely online and was published in his book ''[[The Cathedral and Bazaar]]'' in 1999.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baldwin|first=Carliss Y|author2=Kim Clark |title=The Architecture of Participation: Does Code Architecture Mitigate Free Riding in the Open Source Development Model?|journal=Management Science|date=Jul 2006|volume=52|issue=7|page=1125|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&AuthType=ip,url,cookie,uid&db=bth&AN=21517592&site=ehost-live&scope=site|accessdate=19 March 2014|doi=10.1287/mnsc.1060.0546 }}</ref>

==Contents==
The essay analyzes the economic models that Raymond believes can sustain an open-source project in four steps:<ref>
*{{cite book|last=Samir Chopra|first=Scott D. Dexter|title=Decoding Liberation: The Promise of Free and Open Source Software|year=2007|publisher=Routledge Studies in New Media and Cyberculture|isbn=0415978939|pages=21–23|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aYCQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT39&dq=%22Magic+Cauldron%22+Raymond&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qxMpU9XWHam_0gHFo4HQDQ&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22Magic%20Cauldron%22%20Raymond&f=false}}
*{{cite journal|last=Carmichael|first=Patrick|author2=Leslie Honour |title=Open Source as appropriate technology for global education|journal=International Journal of Educational Development|date=January 2002|volume=22|issue=1|page=50|doi=10.1016/S0738-0593(00)00077-8|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0738059300000778|accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>
* It first analyzes what the author sees as classical myths about the cost refund in software development and tries to present a game-theory based model of the supposed stability of open-source cooperation.
* Secondly, it presents nine theoretical models that would work for sustainable open-source development: two non-profit, seven for-profit.
* Thirdly it states a theory to decide when it is economically interesting for software to remain closed.
* Finally, it examines some mechanisms that, according to Raymond, the market invented to fund for-profit open-source development (like patronage system and task markets).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bruns|first=Bryan|title=Open sourcing nanotechnology research and development: issues and opportunities|journal=Nanotechnology|year=2001|volume=12|issue=3|pages=199, 203|doi=10.1088/0957-4484/12/3/303|url=http://iopscience.iop.org/0957-4484/12/3/303/pdf/0957-4484_12_3_303.pdf|accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>

